# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1874-new-york-mutuals-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1874-new-york-mutuals-season/1873-new-york-mutuals-season] The New York Mutuals base ball team was one of only three teams to have played in all five seasons of the National Association's existence (1871–75).
[src:1874-new-york-mutuals-season/1873-new-york-mutuals-season] In 1873, the team finished the season in fourth place with 29 wins and 24 losses, eleven games behind pennant-winning Boston Red Stockings.
[src:1874-new-york-mutuals-season/1873-new-york-mutuals-season] They won 22 out of 31 home games, played at Union Grounds in Brooklyn, and 7 of 22 away from home.
[src:1874-new-york-mutuals-season/1873-new-york-mutuals-season] The team batting average was .281, which is the fifth-best in the NA.
[src:1874-new-york-mutuals-season/1873-new-york-mutuals-season] They led the league in fewest strikeouts with 22 and fewest opponent runs.
[src:1874-new-york-mutuals-season/1873-new-york-mutuals-season] Starting pitcher Bobby Mathews went 29-23 as a starter with 47 complete games.
[src:1874-new-york-mutuals-season/1873-new-york-mutuals-season] In those complete games, Mathews pitched two shutouts.
[src:1874-new-york-mutuals-season/1873-new-york-mutuals-season] Candy Cummings was the NA's best pitcher in 1872, but decided to go to the Baltimore Canaries, Mathews' former team.
[src:1874-new-york-mutuals-season/1873-new-york-mutuals-season] Nat Hicks, catcher: Played in 28 games played, all catching.
[src:1874-new-york-mutuals-season/1873-new-york-mutuals-season] Joe Start, first baseman, Started his career in 1860 in New York at the age of 18.
[src:1874-new-york-mutuals-season/1873-new-york-mutuals-season] Start is credited with being the 1st first baseman to play away from the bag.
[src:1874-new-york-mutuals-season/1873-new-york-mutuals-season] He had the best fielding average for a first baseman in 1873.
[src:1874-new-york-mutuals-season/1873-new-york-mutuals-season] With 25 games remaining, the Mutuals voted Start to be the manager and he managed the team to a record of 18-7.
[src:1874-new-york-mutuals-season/1873-new-york-mutuals-season] Jim Holdsworth, shortstop: Batted .323 with 28 RBIs in all 53 games for the Mutuals.
[src:1874-new-york-mutuals-season/1873-new-york-mutuals-season] Holdsworth was tied for third in the NA with eight triples.
[src:1874-new-york-mutuals-season/1873-new-york-mutuals-season] John Hatfield, third baseman: Batting .306 with two home runs and 46 RBIs.
[src:1874-new-york-mutuals-season/1873-new-york-mutuals-season] He was the manager of the team for the first 28 games, leading the team to an 11-17 mark.
[src:1874-new-york-mutuals-season/1873-new-york-mutuals-season] Hatfield played in all but one game in 1873.
[src:1874-new-york-mutuals-season/1873-new-york-mutuals-season] Count Gedney, left fielder: Batted .267 with a home run and 24 RBIs in all 53 games for the Mutuals.
[src:1874-new-york-mutuals-season/1873-new-york-mutuals-season] Dave Eggler, center fielder: Batted a .338 with 35 runs batted in and two strikeouts at the plate.
[src:1874-new-york-mutuals-season/1873-new-york-mutuals-season] He had 266 at bats, striking out once every 133 at bats.
[src:1874-new-york-mutuals-season/1873-new-york-mutuals-season] He played in every game in the 1873 season for the Mutuals.
[src:1874-new-york-mutuals-season/1873-new-york-mutuals-season] He was fourth in the NA with 82 runs scored and fifth in fielding runs-outfield.
[src:1874-new-york-mutuals-season/1873-new-york-mutuals-season] He pitched in six games, and lost his only start.
[src:1874-new-york-mutuals-season/1873-new-york-mutuals-season] Martin compiled a 3.44 earned run average and opponents hit .292 against him.
[src:1874-new-york-mutuals-season/1873-new-york-mutuals-season] Dick Higham, utility player: Higham batted .316 with 34 runs batted in 49 games.
[src:1874-new-york-mutuals-season/1873-new-york-mutuals-season] Bobby Mathews batted .193 with 14 runs batted in 223 at bats in 52 games.
[src:1874-new-york-mutuals-season/1873-new-york-mutuals-season] When Mathews wasn't pitching, he would play in right field for reliever Phonney Martin.
[src:1874-new-york-mutuals-season/1874-baltimore-canaries-season] The **Baltimore Canaries** played their final season in 1874 as a member of the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players.
[src:1874-new-york-mutuals-season/1874-baltimore-canaries-season] They finished eighth in the league with a record of 9–38.
[src:1874-new-york-mutuals-season/1874-boston-red-stockings-season] The **1874 Boston Red Stockings season** was the fourth season of the franchise.
[src:1874-new-york-mutuals-season/1874-boston-red-stockings-season] They won their third consecutive National Association championship.
[src:1874-new-york-mutuals-season/1874-boston-red-stockings-season] Managed by Harry Wright, Boston finished with a record of 52–18 to win the pennant by 7.5 games.
[src:1874-new-york-mutuals-season/1874-boston-red-stockings-season] Pitcher Al Spalding started 69 of the Red Stockings' games and led the NA with 52 wins.
[src:1874-new-york-mutuals-season/1874-boston-red-stockings-season] Outfielder Cal McVey led the league with 71 runs batted in, and he paced the Boston offense which scored more runs than any other team.
[src:1874-new-york-mutuals-season/1874-boston-red-stockings-season] Harry Wright, Al Spalding, first baseman Jim O'Rourke, catcher Deacon White, and shortstop George Wright have all been elected into the Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:1874-new-york-mutuals-season/1874-brooklyn-atlantics-season] The **Brooklyn Atlantics** played in 1874 as a member of the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players.
[src:1874-new-york-mutuals-season/1874-brooklyn-atlantics-season] They finished sixth in the league with a record of 22–33.
[src:1874-new-york-mutuals-season/1874-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1874 Chicago White Stockings season** was the third season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the second in the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players and the first at 23rd Street Grounds.
[src:1874-new-york-mutuals-season/1874-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings returned to the league in 1874 after taking two years to recover from the chaos of the Great Chicago Fire.
[src:1874-new-york-mutuals-season/1874-chicago-white-stockings-season] They opened their season on Wednesday May 13 hosting the Philadelphia Athletics and shut them out 4 to 0.
[src:1874-new-york-mutuals-season/1874-chicago-white-stockings-season] They finished fifth in the National Association with a record of 28–31.
[src:1874-new-york-mutuals-season/1874-hartford-dark-blues-season] The Hartford Dark Blues were formed by Morgan Bulkeley and joined the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players for the 1874 season.
[src:1874-new-york-mutuals-season/1874-hartford-dark-blues-season] They finished in seventh place in their debut.
[src:1874-new-york-mutuals-season/1874-major-league-baseball-season] The following are the baseball events of the year 1874 throughout the world.
[src:1874-new-york-mutuals-season/1874-new-york-mutuals-season] The New York Mutuals baseball team finished second in the National Association in 1874.
